Generalization of   to 
other gauges      

The Maximal Abelian Gauge  

The Maximal Abelian gauge (MAG) plays an important role for the dual superconductivity picture
for confinement based on the electromagnetic duality proposed by.
This gauge is extensively used in lattice simulations.
It has provided evidences for the Abelian dominance hypothesis and for
monopoles condensation. In the MAG, the gauge field is decomposed according
to the generators of the Cartan subgroup of the gauge group. For 




For the gauge fixing we have





where  denotes the gauge parameter and





with





The MAG allows for a residual local  invariance, which has
to be fixed later on. It is a nonlinear gauge. As a consequence, a
quartic ghost interaction has to be introduced for consistency
. Lattice simulations have shown that the off-diagonal
components  acquire a mass. These
components should decouple at low energies, according to the
Abelian dominance. Therefore, the understanding of the mechanism
for the dynamical mass generation for the off-diagonal components
is fundamental for the Abelian dominance. It is remarkable that
the operator  of the Landau gauge can be generalized to the
MAG. The gluon-ghost dimension two
operator




has indeed the following property



The condensate  should
play a very important role for the Abelian dominance, as it would provide
effective masses for the off-diagonal components. However, at present, very
little is known about the operator  and the possible
existence of . Concerning the UV
properties of , it has been proven to be multiplicatively
renormalizable.

3mm The Curci-Ferrari gauge     

The so called Curci-Ferrari gauge resembles very much the MAG. It can
thus provide useful insights about the gluon-ghost condensate. For the
gauge fixing we have now
* 
where  for . Notice the presence of
the quartic ghost term. The operator  generalizes
 to the CF gauge as




and



Some properties of the operator  are known. 
 is  multiplicatively renormalizable.
Its anomalous dimension has been computed till three loops in the
 scheme. Recently, the
effective potential for  has been obtained in
, yielding a gap equation whose weak coupling
solution gives a nonvanishing condensate 
, resulting in a dynamical mass generation.
This gives an indication that something similar should happen in
the MAG. It is also worth remarking that the Landau gauge, the MAG
and the CF gauge have many features in common. All these gauges
possess a larger set of global symmetries, giving rise to the so
called Nakanishi-Ojima (NO) algebra. The operators
  are left
invariant(Invariant on-shell for what
concerns the (anti-)BRST.)  by the NO algebra.  

Evidences for ghost condensates  

Contrary to the gauge condensate , the
first proposal for the ghost condensation has been made in the Maximal
Abelian gauge by. Due to the
quartic ghost-antighost self interaction of the MAG




ghosts might condense, giving rise to bound states. To some extent, the
mechanism is similar to the formation of fermion bound states in the Nambu
Jona-Lasinio model. Several channels for the ghost condensates are possible
, corresponding to different values of the Faddeev-Popov charge, namely












The existence of several channels for the ghost condensation
can be related to the dynamical symmetry breaking of the generators of the 
 subalgebra of the NO algebra. It has an interesting
analogy with ordinary superconductivity, known as the BCS versus Overhauser
effect. The BCS channel corresponds to the charged particle-particle and hole-hole pairing,
while the Overhauser to the particle-hole pairing. In the present case the
Faddeev-Popov charged condensates 
, 
 would
correspond to the BCS channel, while 
 to the Overhauser
channel.

Evidences for the existence of the ghost condensates have been reported
also in the Curci-Ferrari gauge. Although the
quartic ghost-antighost interaction is absent in the Landau gauge, it has
been possible by combining the Local Composite Operators technique with the
Algebraic Renormalization to give evidences for the ghost condensation in
this gauge.

Many aspects of the gauge and ghost condensation are under investigation, deserving a deeper understanding.
Some of them are:

 Analysis of the BCS versus Overhauser effect and its relationship
with the breaking of the NO algebra, present in MAG, CF and Landau gauge.

 The role of the color and BRST symmetry in the presence of the gauge
and ghost condensates.

 Modification of the infrared behavior of the ghost propagator and possible
consequences for the Schwinger-Dyson equations. The ghost condensation modifies indeed the
off-diagonal ghost propagator in the infrared as




while for the diagonal component



where  stands for the value of the condensation.
